  "Idea": "The proposed idea introduces Constraint-Induced Neural Execution (CINE), a novel framework that enables pre-trained language models (PLMs) to dynamically generate and execute soft symbolic programs from natural language constraints at inference time, guiding text generation without any task-specific training or auxiliary probe networks. CINE operates by treating each user-specified constraint (e.g., 'Do not mention political affiliations' or 'All events must be in chronological order') as a specification for a latent program, which is compiled on-the-fly into a differentiable expression in a probabilistic lambda calculus defined over a library of typed neural modules (e.g., temporal comparators, sentiment analyzers, entity trackers). These modules are frozen, off-the-shelf components derived from existing models (e.g., spaCy, BERT-based classifiers, rule parsers), but their composition is determined dynamically by the PLM through a process of in-context program induction.\n\nAt each decoding step, the PLM generates not only the next token but also a distribution over possible program continuations conditioned on the current partial output and the natural language constraint. These candidate programs are executed in a differentiable virtual machine (DVM), which computes a soft satisfaction score by evaluating the program against the generated text so far. This score is backpropagated through the DVM to compute gradients with respect to the log-probabilities of future tokens, effectively shaping the generation landscape via constraint-aware policy gradients. Crucially, because the program is induced from natural language and executed symbolically, CINE supports precise hard constraints (via thresholding) and graded soft preferences (via weighted aggregation), while maintaining interpretability and compositional generalization.\n\nCINE fundamentally differs from prior work: unlike UZCI’s reliance on trained probes, CINE requires no meta-training on constraint datasets; unlike Paper 1’s ex-post filtering, CINE integrates constraint reasoning directly into generation; unlike Paper 2’s static knowledge injection, CINE dynamically constructs executable logic; and unlike Paper 3’s loss-refinement approach, CINE preserves the original model weights while introducing external symbolic control. This makes CINE particularly suitable for low-resource, high-stakes domains such as legal drafting, clinical documentation, and ethical AI assistants, where transparency, correctness, and adaptability are paramount.\n\nA key technical contribution is the design of the Differentiable Virtual Machine (DVM), which supports smooth approximations of discrete operations (e.g., set membership, sorting) using kernelized relaxations and stochastic computation graphs. For example, a constraint like 'List symptoms before diagnosis' induces a program that computes a soft inversion count over medical terms, penalizing non-chronological order. Another innovation is in-context program prompting: the PLM is prompted with few-shot examples of constraint-to-program mappings, enabling it to generalize to unseen constraints without fine-tuning. Evaluation will focus on compositional generalization, robustness to paraphrased constraints, and efficiency in long-form generation.",
  "Title": "Constraint-Induced Neural Execution: On-the-Fly Program Synthesis for Zero-Shot Constrained Generation in Language Models",
  "Experiment": "The experimental design consists of three main phases. Phase 1 involves constructing the Differentiable Virtual Machine (DVM) and the library of neural-symbolic primitives. We define a typed functional language with base types (String, Date, Entity, Boolean) and higher-order functions (e.g., forall, exists, sort_by_time). Each primitive (e.g., is_after_date, has_sentiment, contains_entity) is implemented as a frozen differentiable module with soft outputs (e.g., using sigmoidal thresholds or Gaussian kernels for equality). The DVM supports automatic relaxation of discrete operations into continuous proxies (e.g., soft sorting via Sinkhorn iterations).\n\nPhase 2 develops the in-context program induction mechanism. Using GPT-4, we create a synthetic corpus of (natural language constraint, lambda program) pairs across diverse domains (legal, medical, ethical). These are used as few-shot prompts—not for training, but for in-context learning. During inference, the PLM (e.g., LLaMA-3 or Mixtral) receives the input context, the constraint, and 5–8 demonstration pairs, then autoregressively samples both text and program tokens. The generated program is parsed and executed in the DVM to yield a constraint score.\n\nPhase 3 evaluates CINE on three benchmark suites: (a) Structured document generation (e.g., radiology reports with ordering constraints), (b) Ethical dialogue (avoiding harmful content under varying norms), and (c) Temporal narrative consistency. Baselines include UZCI, Prompt+Filter (Paper 1), and Self-Supervised Refinement (Paper 3). Metrics include constraint satisfaction rate (exact and soft), BLEU/ROUGE-L, human coherence评分, and program accuracy (measured via exact match on induced programs when ground truth is available).\n\nPhase 4 tests extreme zero-shot generalization: constraints involving novel compositions (e.g., 'If a drug is mentioned, list side effects within two sentences') or domain shifts (e.g., from medical to financial). We measure cross-domain transfer via constraint embedding similarity and program reuse.\n\nIdeal outcomes: (1) >90% constraint satisfaction on seen and unseen rules, (2) <3% drop in fluency vs unconstrained generation, (3) 40% reduction in invalid outputs compared to filtering-based methods, and (4) high human-rated interpretability of induced programs.",
