  "Idea": "The proposed idea introduces a framework called Unified Zero-Shot Constraint Integration (UZCI), designed to enable pre-trained language models (PLMs) to generate text under both hard logical constraints and soft behavioral preferences without any task-specific training. UZCI leverages two core components: (1) Latent Constraint Probes (LCPs), which are lightweight, input-agnostic neural classifiers that map segments of hidden representations in the PLM to real-valued constraint satisfaction scores, and (2) a Differentiable Logical Composition Layer (DLCL), which combines multiple probe outputs using fuzzy logic operators (e.g., t-norms and co-norms) to compute an overall constraint compliance signal. This signal is then integrated into the decoding process—via modified beam search or nucleus sampling—to guide generation toward outputs that satisfy both mandatory (hard) and desirable (soft) conditions.\n\nUnlike existing approaches that either filter outputs ex-post (Paper 1), inject knowledge during pre-training (Paper 2), or refine loss landscapes (Paper 3), UZCI operates entirely at inference time and requires no retraining of the base model. The LCPs are trained in a meta-learning setup across a broad corpus of synthetically generated constraint-application pairs, where each instance consists of a natural language description of a constraint (e.g., 'All dates must come after January 1, 2020'), a partial context, and a continuation labeled for compliance. Through this, the probes learn to associate linguistic patterns in the hidden states with abstract constraint semantics. At test time, when presented with new constraints described in natural language, the system uses semantic similarity to activate relevant probe subnetworks—even if the exact constraint was not seen during training.\n\nThis approach enables several novel capabilities: first, it supports dynamic constraint composition (e.g., combining temporal consistency with sentiment tone); second, 